st of housing are debated nationally, much of the policymaking surrounding these issues occurs locally. In Local Interests, Sarah F. Anzia explores how local governments—and the interest groups that try to influence them—create the policies that drive the national conversation: policing, economic development, housing, and challenges of taxing and spending. Anzia examines local interest groups in terms of the specific policies they pursue, including how these groups get active in politics and what impact they have. By offering new perspectives on these issues, Anzia contributes to our knowledge of how interest groups function and the significant role they play in shaping broader social outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEconomic developmentxCitizen participation. 0aEconomic developmentzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aHousing policyzUnited StatesvPeriodicals. 0aHousing policyzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aLocal governmentzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aPolice administrationxCitizen participation. 0aPolice administrationzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aPublic interest groupszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  alocal politics, local government, interest group, public policy, city, partisan, police, business, union, housing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2